<dl id="n03144f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n03" href="#n03144f">N03 (VI.B.3)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n03all.htm#n03144f"> 144(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> poacher&apos;s death <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n03144f"> <li>FW unlocated</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The Ordeal by Red-hot Iron]</font> Now, gentles, as Perinis returned towards Tintagel, he perceived in a thicket the same forester who had formerly surprised the sleeping lovers and denounced them to the king. &hellip; this man had dug a deep pit in the earth, which he had covered skillfully with branches, <mark>to snare</mark> wolves and boars. He saw the Queen&apos;s servant bounding topwards him, and tried to fly. But Perinis pressed him back to the edge of the pit: &ldquo;Spy who betrayed the Queen, why wouldst thou fly? Stay here by the grave which thou hast digged for thyself!&rdquo; His cudgel hummed in the air as he whirled it round. <mark>Cudgel and skull cracked</mark> at the same moment, and Perinis the Fair-haired, the Faithful, spurned the corpse with his foot into the pit. <small> Joseph B&eacute;dier, <a name="JBLR1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JBLR1"><cite title="source">Le roman de Tristan et Iseut</cite></a> (1900) XII &lsquo;Le Jugement par le Fer Rouge&rsquo;, 135</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
